Note:
==============================================================================
UUID - Universally Unique Identifier (RFC 9562 / formerly RFC 4122)
==============================================================================

A UUID is a 128-bit identifier. This module implements every variant
defined in RFC 9562 (which obsoletes RFC 4122 and adds v6, v7, v8):

  UUIDv1 - time-based (60-bit gregorian time + clock seq + node)
  UUIDv3 - name-based, MD5 hash of (namespace || name)
  UUIDv4 - random (122 random bits)
  UUIDv5 - name-based, SHA-1 hash of (namespace || name)
  UUIDv6 - reordered time-based (lexicographically sortable)
  UUIDv7 - Unix epoch ms + random (DB-friendly, the new recommended)
  UUIDv8 - application-defined

References:
- RFC 9562: Universally Unique IDentifiers (UUID)
- IETF draft-peabody-dispatch-new-uuid-format (precursor to RFC 9562)
- RFC 1321: The MD5 Message-Digest Algorithm (for UUIDv3)
- FIPS PUB 180-4: Secure Hash Standard (SHA-1 for UUIDv5)

Memory layout for UUID (16 bytes, raw bytes per RFC 9562):
  bytes 0-3:   time_low / random / hash
  bytes 4-5:   time_mid / random / hash
  bytes 6-7:   time_hi_and_version (4-bit version + 12-bit data)
  bytes 8:     clock_seq_hi_and_reserved (2-bit variant + 6-bit data)
  bytes 9:     clock_seq_low / random / hash
  bytes 10-15: node / random / hash

The Bytes primitive is reused as the carrier; uuid.runa exposes a
typed alias UUID = Bytes-of-16.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StrCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/bytes.runa" as Bytes
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/syscall.runa" as Syscall

Constant UUID_SIZE as Integer is 16

Note: ============================================================================
Note: INTERNAL: Bytes-of-16 construction
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "uuid_internal_alloc" returns Integer:
    Let buf be allocate(UUID_SIZE)
    If buf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Memory.memory_fill(buf, 0, UUID_SIZE)
    Return buf
End Process

Process called "uuid_internal_set_version_variant" takes buf as Integer, version as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Set 4-bit version in the upper nibble of byte 6.
    Let cur6 be Memory.memory_get_byte(buf, 6)
    Let lower4 be cur6 minus ((cur6 divided by 16) multiplied by 16)
    Let new6 be (version multiplied by 16) plus lower4
    Memory.memory_set_byte(buf, 6, new6)
    Note: Set variant (RFC 9562 variant 10xx) in upper 2 bits of byte 8.
    Let cur8 be Memory.memory_get_byte(buf, 8)
    Let lower6 be cur8 minus ((cur8 divided by 64) multiplied by 64)
    Let new8 be 128 plus lower6
    Memory.memory_set_byte(buf, 8, new8)
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: INTERNAL: SIMPLE TIME / RANDOM SOURCES
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "uuid_internal_read_clock_ns" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Reads the current monotonic timestamp in nanoseconds via the
        clock_gettime syscall (linux x86-64 syscall 228). Returns 0
        on failure. This is sufficient for UUIDv1/v6/v7 timestamp
        derivation without pulling in the full time_utils stack.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Allocate a 16-byte timespec, syscall(228, CLOCK_REALTIME=0,
        timespec_ptr), read seconds and nanos, combine.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Single syscall.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Timestamps are not secrets; this proc never reads kernel data
        beyond the timespec it allocated.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let timespec be allocate(16)
    If timespec is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Memory.memory_fill(timespec, 0, 16)
    Let syscall_result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # syscall_2 inlined: rax=228 (clock_gettime), rdi=0 (REALTIME), rsi=timespec
        movq $228, %rax
        movq $0, %rdi
        movq -8(%rbp), %rsi
        syscall
        movq %rax, -16(%rbp)
    End Assembly
    If syscall_result is less than 0:
        deallocate(timespec)
        Return 0
    End If
    Let secs be Memory.memory_get_integer(timespec, 0)
    Let nanos be Memory.memory_get_integer(timespec, 8)
    deallocate(timespec)
    Let ns_total be (secs multiplied by 1000000000) plus nanos
    Return ns_total
End Process

Process called "uuid_internal_read_urandom" takes buf as Integer, len as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Fills `len` bytes of `buf` with cryptographic-quality random
        data from the kernel CSPRNG via the cross-platform syscall
        dispatcher. Returns 1 on success, 0 on failure. The dispatcher
        routes to getrandom(2) on Linux/BSD/MIPS/RISC-V/PowerPC and
        getentropy(2) on Darwin/OpenBSD; both are seeded from the
        kernel's ChaCha20-based pool. The proc name is preserved for
        callers but no longer reads /dev/urandom directly - the kernel
        CSPRNG is reached without an open/read/close round-trip.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Delegates to Syscall.secure_random_bytes. The dispatcher
        selects the platform-correct syscall number at runtime via
        the register_map backend index, so no Linux x86-64 syscall
        numbers leak into this module.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        One syscall on getrandom platforms; ceil(len/256) syscalls on
        getentropy platforms (a single syscall for the 16-byte UUID
        workload).
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Cryptographically strong on every supported platform with a
        wired CSPRNG primitive. Windows currently returns -1 from the
        dispatcher (BCryptGenRandom FFI not yet bound); on Windows the
        caller observes the failure and refuses to emit a predictable
        UUID rather than silently substituting weaker randomness.
    @End Security_Scope

    If buf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If len is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If len is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If
    Let written be proc secure_random_bytes from Syscall with buf, len
    If written is less than len:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "uuid_internal_fill_random" takes buf as Integer, len as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Primary entropy source for every UUID variant that mixes
        random bits. Returns 1 on success, 0 on failure. The kernel
        CSPRNG path through Syscall.secure_random_bytes is the only
        accepted source: if it fails, this proc reports failure so
        the caller can refuse to emit a non-cryptographic UUID. The
        previous xorshift fallback was removed because it produced
        predictable bytes while the surrounding @Security_Scope
        claimed CSPRNG quality - a silent downgrade that broke the
        documented security guarantee.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Single call to uuid_internal_read_urandom which dispatches
        through the platform-aware Syscall module.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        One syscall per UUID on the fast path.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Hard-fails when the kernel CSPRNG is unreachable; never
        substitutes a deterministic PRNG.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return uuid_internal_read_urandom(buf, len)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MD5 - RFC 1321 (used by UUIDv3 only; not exposed as public API)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "uuid_internal_md5_rotl" takes x as Integer, n as Integer returns Integer:
    Let mask be 4294967295
    Let masked be x bitwise and mask
    Let left be (masked multiplied by 1)
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than n:
        Set left to left multiplied by 2
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Let left_low be left bitwise and mask
    Let right be masked divided by 1
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than (32 minus n):
        Set right to right divided by 2
        Set j to j plus 1
    End While
    Return left_low bitwise or right
End Process

Process called "uuid_internal_md5_F" takes x as Integer, y as Integer, z as Integer returns Integer:
    Let mask_xor_z be y bitwise xor z
    Let mid be x bitwise and mask_xor_z
    Return mid bitwise xor z
End Process

Process called "uuid_internal_md5_G" takes x as Integer, y as Integer, z as Integer returns Integer:
    Let xz be x bitwise and z
    Let not_z be (4294967295 minus z) bitwise and 4294967295
    Let yz be y bitwise and not_z
    Return xz bitwise or yz
End Process

Process called "uuid_internal_md5_H" takes x as Integer, y as Integer, z as Integer returns Integer:
    Let xy be x bitwise xor y
    Return xy bitwise xor z
End Process

Process called "uuid_internal_md5_I" takes x as Integer, y as Integer, z as Integer returns Integer:
    Let not_z be (4294967295 minus z) bitwise and 4294967295
    Let xz be x bitwise or not_z
    Return y bitwise xor xz
End Process

Process called "uuid_internal_md5_K" takes i as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: RFC 1321 K[i] = floor(2^32 * |sin(i+1)|). Compute lookup at runtime
    Note: by table since we have no float sin in primitives.
